@node intro "CheckLink / Introduction"

  - Introduction -

  CheckLink is a program I have written because I was completely
  fed up of fixing my Web pages for broken links.

  Even if I checked my Web pages locally, porting them on my
  provider's Hard Disk, would cause some of them not to work because
  my provider works with Unix machines, and that DOS do make
  distimption between UPPER and lower chars.

  So, while on my beloved Amiga everything used to work fine,
  mirroring my data on that Silicon Graphics used to create
  problems.

  Not more. :)

  Now using my CheckLink, I am able to check all my HTML files agains
  broken links, and, guys, it is incredibly smart!!
  
  See @{" Features " LINK "features"} for a brief list of important
  features in CheckLink.

  If you own a Web Site on a Unix machine, CheckLink will be *THE*
  tool you need!

  NOTE: CheckLink is *email-ware*, please take your time to send me
        an e-mail if you use it. 

@endnode

@node features "CheckLink - Features"

  Features

  - Extremely fast.

  - Reliable.

  - Checks for links in hrefs, maps, frames...

  - Checks for images.

  - Understands also "Mailto:", "http:", "PROGDIR:", CGI Scripts, PERL scripts...

  - Recursive (scans _all_ files related to the first one).

  - Smart: does not check a file twice.

  - Configurable.

  - Support @{" External Reference File " LINK ext_ref} for more accuracy.

@endnode

@node usage "CheckLink - Usage"

  Usage

  CheckLink is a Shell program.
  This means that you must type some chars on a Shell to see CheckLink at work.

  Here there is its template:

  FILE/A      - It is the (starting) file to check.

  NOCASE/S    - If provided, CheckLink will *not* perform Case Sensitive check,
                but will just tell you if a linked file exists or not.

  NORECURSE/S - If provided, will tell CheckLink to control *only* the file 
                provided and not to check also all related files.

                By default, CheckLink will scan all the file and,
                while checking the links, it stores them for scan'em later.
                This is a recursive operation, which means that this work
                is done for *all* links in *all* pages.

                It will not check a page twice, anyway :-)

  VERBOSE/S   - CheckLink is smarter that it seems. Just try to provide
                this switch and you'll see why.

  LOGFILE/K   - If you provide this command line, you have to specify
                a file name, where the LOGFILE will be saved.

                Eg. CheckLink test.html LOGFILE="Ram:Report"

  QUIET/S     - If you provide this switch no messages will be prompted
                to the Shell. Use it in conjuction with LOGFILE.

  CREATEEXT/S - If this switch is provided, then all "external" links, such as
                "http://", "news:", "mailto:" that are referenced inside your
                pages will be stored inside a file (you can define the name
                with the "EXTLINKS" argument (see below)).
                For more info, please, read the @{" External Reference List " LINK ext_ref} section.

  EXTLINKS/K  - Use this argument to provide a name for the @{" External Reference List " LINK ext_ref}
                file name.

  Here there are some examples of CheckLink usage:


  CheckLink main.html VERBOSE >ram:check.txt

    This example will load "main.html" file (and all related html files) and check it
    against errors. CheckLink will say a lot of stuff (VERBOSE is set) and all the
    output is sent to the file "check.txt" in Ram Disk.
    (Note: this is the way I use it, usually)

  CheckLink main.html NOCASE >ram:check.txt

    This time CheckLink will do check just file existance without saying anything
    more than just reporting broken links.

  CheckLink main.html NORECURSE VERBOSE

    And with this command line, CheckLink will check *just* main.html
    reporting errors on the active Shell.


@endnode

@node ext_ref "CheckLink - External Reference List"

  External Reference List

  Starting from V1.40, CheckLink supports an external file called
  @{i}External Reference List@{ui}, which is a file containing a
  list of external references, such as "http://...", "mailto:..." 
  and so on that CheckLink is not able to check by itself.

  You can create this reference list by simply starting CheckLink
  with the @{b}CREATEEXT@{ub} command line argument. In this way, every
  new external link will be added to a file called "CheckLink_references"
  and stored in the same dir where CheckLink is.

  You can also provide an alternative name/path to the default one
  using the @{b}EXTLINKS@{ub} command line argument.

  To use the @{i}External Reference List@{ui}, you should pass the
  @{b}VERBOSE@{ub} flag into the command line. From now on, whenever
  an external link is encountered, you'll see a line like this:

  NOTE:    Line: 00012 - (*ADDED*) "MAILTO:" reference: mailto:fsoft@intercom.it

  You should pay attention to the word inside the two parentesys.
  The word can be:

    *ADDED* - The link is encountered for the first time and you have provided the
              @{b}CREATEEXT@{ub} command line argument, then this new link has been
              added to the list.

    CHECKED - The link is already present in the list and it correctly matches the
              one in the list.

    UNCHECK - The link is not present in the list and you have not provieded the 
              @{b}CREATEEXT@{ub} command line argument, so it cannot be added to
              the list. It could be a valid or a wrong link... who knows?

    -WRONG- - The link is present in the list, the current one matches but it is
              mispelled (wrong case of text...)
              This error will not occur if you provide the @{b}NOCASE@{ub} command
              line argument.

  NOTE: you can use the @{b}CREATEEXT@{ub} command line argument any time you want
        because it will not delete the old file link for the new one, instead, it
        will add new links to the existing ones.

@endnode

